In .NET MAUI, you use the **lifecycle events API** on `MauiAppBuilder` via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:

```csharp
// In MauiProgram.cs
using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;

public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

    builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
    {
#if ANDROID
        events.AddAndroid(android => android
            .OnPause(activity => { /* runs on Android pause */ })
            .OnStop(activity => { /* runs on Android stop */ }));
#endif

#if IOS
        events.AddiOS(ios => ios
            .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* runs on iOS background */ }));
#endif
    });

    return builder.Build();
}
```

**Key points:**

- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#if IOS` platform guards.
- `AddAndroid` exposes `OnPause`, `OnStop`, `OnResume`, `OnDestroy`, etc.
- `AddiOS` exposes `DidEnterBackground`, `WillEnterForeground`, `WillTerminate`, etc.
- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;` for the extension methods.

This is the recommended cross-platform pattern — no custom platform renderers or `Activity`/`AppDelegate` subclasses needed.
